<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Are Monks Any Good in PvP? </b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
I get asked this a lot, and the short answer is yes, Monks are good in PvP. However, several factors other than the class go into whether monks are &quot;good&quot; at PvP, these being (in order of importance):<br>
<br>
1. Skill<br>
1. Level<br>
2. Resist Gear<br>
2. Normal Gear<br>
3. Primal Weapon (yes, this has its own category. it only applies to the 50+ PvP scene though.)  <br>
3. Movement Speed (pumice, SoW, jboots, etc)<br>
4. Regeneration<br>
5. AA abilities (other than improved run 3) <br>
<br>
If you have these all on your side, then yes you can be a hell of a PK'er as a Monk. Its not an easy class to play, or start untwinked as on a PvP server though. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>  Jousting</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--><br>
<br>
You don't go toe-to-toe with melee's on a PvP server. Instead you &quot;joust&quot;, which is exactly what it sounds like.  Best strategy to use when jousting, it to strafe to the right or left right before passing your opponent, and quickly hit him with FK/autoattack/disarm. If you're getting beat down, go on the defensive, make your opponent charge you and use the strafing-joust technique. If you're outmatched by your opponent, stay defensive and make them charge you, then evade it and hit them. Try to make your jousting patterns unpredictable, rather than just blindly charging your opponent over and over. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>    Fighting specific classes with a Monk</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    Warriors &amp; Paladins</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
They have more HP and sometimes more AC than you, and have a lot of high damage weapons available. A fight with them will be largely dependant on your skill in jousting. Most fights with warriors I've had have been pretty close, remember to always use flying kick when jousting and use mend as soon as you get below 70% HP. The longer the fight takes, the better chance you have of winning because mend will eventually give you the advantage. Counter Mighty Strike discipline (if they use it) with Whirlwind. Same tactics apply to fighting a Paladin, but be sure to pumice the Paladin as soon as you can (cancelling their HP buffs can knock off a lot of HP &amp; AC) and make them lay hands as soon as possible so you can retreat if you are losing and effectively waste their Lay Hands. A 58+ Pally with full mana is damn near unkillable because of the DoT Heal they get which cast in about a second and heals a lot. Paladins are very hard to actually kill since they can heal themselves in so many ways. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    Shadowknights</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
SK's are a bitch, plain and simple. You're gonna need at least 80 MR, a see invis item, pumice stone(s). If they land a darkness on you, you can pretty much consider the fight over - so wear some MR gear but don't sacrifice too much AC/HP for it. I've never fought a SK who used his pet when fighting me, most seem to favor using a pre-nerf CoS which can be deadly if you don't have a see-invis item on. Fight them like a warrior, but watch out for Harm Touch. Sometimes its best not to use Mend as soon as you get below 70% HP when fighting a SK, wait for them to HT instead.. but not too long to where the HT will outright kill you. If you can't win the fight after they hit you with Harm Touch, retreat and come back to a much easier fight. Don't let the SK get too far away from you, you don't want them getting distance on you and hitting you with DoT's or what not. If you score a victory over an equal or higher level SK, then give yourself a pat on the back cause it won't happen often. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    Rogues</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <br>
<br>
Fight them like a warrior, don't let them get behind your back. Wear a see-invis item, otherwise they're going to pelt you with backstabs and/or poison. Don't joust them straight up, good rogues know how to do a foward-backstab, so try to get on the side of them. Also, take your time when fighting a rogue, don't attempt going toe-to-toe with them. Stay defensive. Once you get careless, they start landing backstabs. Rogues are weak at jousting if you take away their backstab. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    Bards</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Annoying as hell. You can't win against them in outdoor areas, enough said. Indoors they are a shitty Ranger and a peice of cake. Anyway, if you have a TStaff and get lucky with procs and innerflame, you MIGHT be able to kill one outdoors. Otherwise, just boost up your MR, FR, and CR (90+ in all three is good) and they can't do jack shit to you (unless they are decked out in North ToV gear or have levels on you). Resists are the key to not losing against a Bard, but there's just no good strategy to actually killing them. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    Enchanters &amp; Wizards</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
When fighting a Chanter, sacrifice everything for MR. Tashania takes off a lot of MR. No MR? You are dead.  Same thing applies to Wizards, except you need FR and CR too. For both classes, fast weapons will work best for killing them. Pumice stones also do some good to get rid of lev/shielding/etc. Wizards and Chanters have very low HP &amp; AC, stick to them and don't let them get any spells off. Of course a level 60 Wizzie or Chanter can channel through almost anything, but you still stand a better chance of interupting them. Yonder can be annoying, but its not too hard to spot where they land unless you're fighting on hilly terrain. Again, if your MR sucks they will school you. Recently Implemented was the wonderful Wizard-only AA skill Manaburn, this is an instant death for almost anyone. When Verant implemented this skill I'm sure they didn't give PvP servers half a thought because a Manaburning Wizard can kill anybody in one shot now.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    Druids</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
You need: many a pumice stone, very high MR &amp; FR. Start off the fight by using your pumice stone untill SoW/thorns drop. Winged Death is not nerfed in PvP, and it also stacks with Drifting Death. These DoTs are also basically unresistable and a Druid's primary killing tool, even at 60. If Winged Death lands on you pumice it immediately. The key to killing a Druid is to not let them land their DoTs, stick to them as close as you can. Having good FR helps a lot too, since all of their nukes are fire based and they can debuff your FR. Thorns + heals will enable you to basically kill yourself, so always use pumice untill thorns are gone. A Druid with his SoW/levitate/thorns buried deep below other buffs, who knows how to play his class can be a nightmare for a Monk. Don't let them get out of melee range. If you're equipped with a lot of pumice stones and half decent resists though, its hard to die to a Druid. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    Necros &amp; Magicians</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Stick to the caster, don't worry about the pet. You can try instill doubting, but its way too unreliable from my experience. Dispelling the pet (hard to do, but possible) will make life much easier while fighting a Mage as their pets can still put a dent on your HP's even 50+. The epic pet will tear you up. Necro pets are pretty weak even at 60, never go for a necro pet instead of fighting the Necro. Monks can't really factor the pet out of the equation like most classes can via Root or Snare, so you won't have an easy fight against either a Necro or Magician. Almost all the high-end Necro DoTs are dispellable, and its best to dispell them immediately because they pack a hell of a punch. Fortunately they drop fast just like Wizards, just stay close to them and don't fight the pet first. Necros have the AA ability Lifeburn now, this is the Necro equivalent of Manaburn and is just as overpowered in PvP.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    Shamans</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Its impossible to get rid of a Shaman's SoW if he has Black Fur Boots (easily obtained instant cast SoW). Most likely, his pet will have SoW too. Shaman pets don't do much damage, you don't really have to worry about them. You need: Pumice stone, lots of MR PR DR CR. Resists are the key here, you need to max them out when fighting a Shaman.  If Ebolt and/or Plague lands on you, its over. They aren't very deadly untill 60 when they get Malo (unresistable 50+ debuff to all resists - dispell it immediately if they use it), but still a huge pain in the ass to kill no matter what level. Fight them like you would a Druid. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>   Rangers </b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
You need good MR, pumice stones. Get rid of their buffs, resist ensnare, and don't let them bow-kite you and you'll have one hell of an easy fight. Their nukes can hurt, especially 52+ so high FR does help. 60 Rangers with a good bow, Archery Mastery, and Trueshot *will* kill you in a matter of seconds if you let them. A Ranger with thorns buried deep and a good jousting weapon (Rangers I see more than any other class using 1h weapons even when jousting) are often underestimated and can kill you too despite the common stereotype that Rangers just suck at everything. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>   Clerics </b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
You need high MR and pumice. Clerics are not meant to be a PvP class and really can't do any significant damage. They rely on nukes, and melee damage (yes you heard that right). Root won't land unless they have levels or your MR is crappy, and most of the times nukes won't do full damage. Despite this, they are probably the hardest class to kill in PvP next to Bards. Their heals are extremely efficient,  they do have good AC/HP, and Divine Aura. With a very good 2hb, and nukes they can actually get kills sometimes, so don't get careless.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>   Beastlord </b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Almost the same as Magicians, except they can take more of a beating. The pet is on par with Mage pets, so they will do damage to you. Beastlords themselves don't dish out much damage. The problem for Monks here is that the pet and the owner will both be SoW'd, so again you have to manage to pumice the owner's SoW off and take him out. Feign Death the pet off, instill doubt it, or get lucky with misses so you can pumice him. Whatever you do, don't try to take out the pet - it's not gonna happen. Not with the pet heals they get, plus they will wisen up and begin beating on you along with their pet. Not a particulary good PvP class from my experience, especially at the high end game. <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    Player-Killing on a PvP Server</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Most fights occur when you don't expect them to, so its a good idea to keep at least some resist gear on at all times. <br>
<br>
The main factor in whether you win a fight or not on a PvP server is if you find your opponent, or if he finds you.<br>
<br>
Don't pick fights you can't win, not gonna go into detail here. <br>
<br>
Don't talk shit in OOC / Shout excessively, as it just makes you look dumb. <br>
<br>
Don't be a lamer, if you kill someone let them loot their corpse and leave. If you get killed, loot your corpse and leave for a while. Don't train on people, or attack them while they're fighting a mob. <br>
 <br>
Some people opt for high AC or resists over Regeneration (fungi tunic), but the regeneration will help you more in PvP than any other single factor. It can be a lifesaver in long fights and give you an advantage over the opponent. 3 AA points into both Improved Run Speed and Improved Regeneration will help a lot in PvP. <br>
<br>
When PK'ing, have:<br>
- Jboots or Improved Run 3<br>
- SoW Potions <br>
- A fast weapon<br>
- A high damage weapon<br>
- Pumice Stones (19pp at many vendors, 5 charge nullify magic)<br>
- Resist gear (see below) <br>
- Bandages<br>
- Little money on you <br>
<br>
